# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: requestanimationframe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:requestanimationframe/cancelanimationframe] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:requestanimationframe/cancelanimationframe] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:requestanimationframe/cancelanimationframe] The **`window.cancelAnimationFrame()`** method cancels an animation frame request previously scheduled through a call to `window.requestAnimationFrame()`.
[src:requestanimationframe/cancelanimationframe] The ID value returned by the call to `window.requestAnimationFrame()` that requested the callback.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer animation is a digital successor to stop motion and traditional animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Instead of a physical model or illustration, a digital equivalent is manipulated frame-by-frame.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Also, computer-generated animations allow a single graphic artist to produce such content without using actors, expensive set pieces, or props.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] To create the illusion of movement, an image is displayed on the computer monitor and repeatedly replaced by a new similar image but advanced slightly in time (usually at a rate of 24, 25, or 30 frames per second).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] This technique is identical to how the illusion of movement is achieved with television and motion pictures.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] To trick the visual system into seeing a smoothly moving object, the pictures should be drawn at around 12 frames per second (which, when animating on 24 frames per second, is called "animating on twos”) or faster (a frame is one complete image).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] At rates below 12 frames per second, most people can detect jerkiness associated with the drawing of new images that detracts from the illusion of realistic movement.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Conventional hand-drawn cartoon animation often uses 15 frames per second in order to save on the number of drawings needed, but this is usually accepted because of the stylized nature of cartoons.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] To produce more realistic imagery, computer animation demands higher frame rates.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Films seen in theaters in the United States run at 24 frames per second, which is sufficient to create the appearance of continuous movement.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer-generated animation is an umbrella term for three-dimensional (3D) animation, and 2D computer animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] These also include subcategories like asset driven, hybrid, and digital drawn animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Creators animate using code or software instead of pencil-to-paper drawings.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] There are many techniques and disciplines in computer generated animation, some of which are digital representations of traditional animation - such as key frame animation - and some of which are only possible with a computer - such fluid simulation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] 'CG' Animators can break physical laws by using mathematical algorithms to cheat mass, force and gravity, and more.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer-generated animation is a powerful tool which can improve the quality of animation by using the power of computing to unleash the animator's imagination.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] This is because computer-generated animation allows for things like onion skinning which allows 2D animators to see the flow of their work all at once, and interpolation which allows 3D animators to automate the process of inbetweening.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] For 3D computer animations, objects (models) are built on the computer monitor (modeled) and 3D figures are rigged with a virtual skeleton.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Then the limbs, eyes, mouth, clothes, etc. of the figure are moved by the animator on key frames.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Normally, the differences between key frames are drawn in a process known as tweening.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] However, in 3D computer animation, this is done automatically, and is called interpolation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Finally, the animation is rendered and composited.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Before becoming a final product, 3D computer animations only exist as a series of moving shapes and systems within 3D software, and must be rendered.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] This can happen as a separate process for animations developed for movies and short films, or it can be done in real-time when animated for videogames.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] After an animation is rendered, it can be composited into a final product.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] For 3D models, attributes can describe any characteristic of the object that can be animated.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] This includes transformation (movement from one point to another), scaling, rotation, and more complex attributes like blend shape progression (morphing from one shape to another).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Each attribute gets a channel on which keyframes can be set.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] These keyframes can be used in more complex ways such as animating in layers (combining multiple sets of key frame data), or keying control objects to deform or control other objects.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] For instance, a character's arms can have a skeleton applied, and the joints can have transformation and rotation keyframes set.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The movement of the arm joints will then cause the arm shape to deform.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] 3D animation software interpolates between keyframes by generating a spline between keys plotted on a graph which represents the animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Additionally, these splines can follow Bézier curves to control how the spline curves relative to the keyframes.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Using interpolation allows 3D animators to dynamically change animations without having to redo all the in-between animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] This also allows the creation of complex movements such as ellipses with only a few keyframes.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Lastly, interpolation allows the animator to change the framerate, timing, and even scale of the movements at any point in the animation process.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Another way to automate 3D animation is to use procedural tools such as 4D noise.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Noise is any algorithm that plots pseudo-random values within a dimensional space.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] 4D noise can be used to do things like move a swarm of bees around; the first three dimensions correspond to the position of the bees in space, and the fourth is used to change the bee's position over time.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Noise can also be used as a cheap replacement for simulation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] For example, smoke and clouds can be animated using noise.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Node-based animation is useful for animating organic and chaotic shapes.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] By using nodes, an animator can build up a complex set of animation rules that can be applied either to many objects at once, or one very complex object.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] A good example of this would be setting the movement of particles to match the beat of a song.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] There are many different disciplines of 3D animation, some of which include entirely separate artforms.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] For example, hair simulation for computer animated characters in and of itself is a career path which involves separate workflows, and different software and tools.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The combination of all or some 3D computer animation disciplines is commonly referred to within the animation industry as the 3D animation pipeline.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] 2D computer graphics are still used for stylistic, low bandwidth, and faster real-time renderings.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer animation is essentially a digital successor to stop motion techniques, but using 3D models, and traditional animation techniques using frame-by-frame animation of 2D illustrations.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] For 2D figure animations, separate objects (illustrations) and separate transparent layers are used with or without that virtual skeleton.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In 2D computer animation, moving objects are often referred to as "sprites." A sprite is an image that has a location associated with it.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The location of the sprite is changed slightly, between each displayed frame, to make the sprite appear to move.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer-assisted animation is usually classed as two-dimensional (2D) animation and is also known as digital ink and paint.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Drawings are either hand drawn (pencil to paper) or interactively drawn (on the computer) using different assisting appliances and are positioned into specific software packages.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Within the software package, the creator places drawings into different key frames which fundamentally create an outline of the most important movements.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The computer then fills in the "in-between frames", a process commonly known as tweening.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer-assisted animation employs new technologies to produce content faster than is possible with traditional animation, while still retaining the stylistic elements of traditionally drawn characters or objects.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] A Dinosaur's Story*, *Balto*, *Anastasia*, *Titan A.E.*, *The Prince of Egypt*, *The Road to El Dorado*, *Spirit: Stallion of the Cimarron* and *Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas*.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Early digital computer animation was developed at Bell Telephone Laboratories in the 1960s by Edward E.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Other digital animation was also practiced at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In 1967, a computer animation named "Hummingbird" was created by Charles Csuri and James Shaffer.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In 1968, a computer animation called "Kitty" was created with BESM-4 by Nikolai Konstantinov, depicting a cat moving around.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In 1971, a computer animation called "Metadata" was created, showing various shapes.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] An early step in the history of computer animation was the sequel to the 1973 film *Westworld,* a science-fiction film about a society in which robots live and work among humans.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The sequel, *Futureworld* (1976), used the 3D wire-frame imagery, which featured a computer-animated hand and face both created by University of Utah graduates Edwin Catmull and Fred Parke.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] This imagery originally appeared in their student film *A Computer Animated Hand*, which they completed in 1972.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Developments in CGI technologies are reported each year at SIGGRAPH, an annual conference on computer graphics and interactive techniques that is attended by thousands of computer professionals each year.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Developers of computer games and 3D video cards strive to achieve the same visual quality on personal computers in real-time as is possible for CGI films and animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] With the rapid advancement of real-time rendering quality, artists began to use game engines to render non-interactive movies, which led to the art form Machinima.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] CGI short films have been produced as independent animation since 1976.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Early examples of feature films incorporating CGI animation include the live-action films *Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan* and *Tron* (both 1982), and the Japanese anime film *Golgo 13: The Professional* (1983).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] *VeggieTales* is the first American fully 3D computer-animated series sold directly (made in 1993); its success inspired other animation series, such as *ReBoot* (1994) and *Transformers: Beast Wars* (1996) to adopt a fully computer-generated style.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The first full-length computer-animated television series was *ReBoot*, which debuted in September 1994; the series followed the adventures of characters who lived inside a computer.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The first feature-length computer-animated film is *Toy Story* (1995), which was made by Disney and Pixar: following an adventure centered around anthropomorphic toys and their owners, this groundbreaking film was also the first of many fully computer-animated movies.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The popularity of computer animation (especially in the field of special effects) skyrocketed during the modern era of U.S. animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Films like *Avatar* (2009) and *The Jungle Book* (2016) use CGI for the majority of the movie runtime, but still incorporate human actors into the mix.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer animation in this era has achieved photorealism, to the point that computer-animated films such as *The Lion King* (2019) are able to be marketed as if they were live-action.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In most 3D computer animation systems, an animator creates a simplified representation of a character's anatomy, which is analogous to a skeleton or stick figure.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] They are arranged into a default position known as a bind pose, or T-Pose.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The position of each segment of the skeletal model is defined by animation variables, or Avars for short.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In human and animal characters, many parts of the skeletal model correspond to the actual bones, but skeletal animation is also used to animate other things, with facial features (though other methods for facial animation exist).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The character Woody in *Toy Story*, for example, uses 712 Avars (212 in the face alone).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The computer does not usually render the skeletal model directly (it is invisible), but it does use the skeletal model to compute the exact position and orientation of that certain character, which is eventually rendered into an image.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Thus by changing the values of Avars over time, the animator creates motion by making the character move from frame to frame.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] There are several methods for generating the Avar values to obtain realistic motion.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Traditionally, animators manipulate the Avars directly.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Rather than set Avars for every frame, they usually set Avars at strategic points (frames) in time and let the computer interpolate or tween between them in a process called *keyframing*.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Keyframing puts control in the hands of the animator and has roots in hand-drawn traditional animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In contrast, a newer method called *motion capture* makes use of live action footage.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] When computer animation is driven by motion capture, a real performer acts out the scene as if they were the character to be animated.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Their motion is recorded to a computer using video cameras and markers and that performance is then applied to the animated character.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Each method has its advantages and as of 2007, games and films are using either or both of these methods in productions.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Keyframe animation can produce motions that would be difficult or impossible to act out, while motion capture can reproduce the subtleties of a particular actor.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] For example, in the 2006 film *Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest*, Bill Nighy provided the performance for the character Davy Jones.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Even though Nighy does not appear in the movie himself, the movie benefited from his performance by recording the nuances of his body language, posture, facial expressions, etc.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Thus motion capture is appropriate in situations where believable, realistic behavior and action is required, but the types of characters required exceed what can be done throughout the conventional costuming.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] 3D computer animation combines 3D models of objects and programmed or hand "keyframed" movement.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] These models are constructed out of geometrical vertices, faces, and edges in a 3D coordinate system.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Objects are sculpted much like real clay or plaster, working from general forms to specific details with various sculpting tools.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Unless a 3D model is intended to be a solid color, it must be painted with "textures" for realism.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] A bone/joint animation system is set up to deform the CGI model (e.g., to make a humanoid model walk).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In a process known as *rigging*, the virtual marionette is given various controllers and handles for controlling movement.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Animation data can be created using motion capture, or keyframing by a human animator, or a combination of the two.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] 3D models rigged for animation may contain thousands of control points — for example, "Woody" from *Toy Story* uses 700 specialized animation controllers.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Rhythm and Hues Studios labored for two years to create Aslan in the movie *The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe*, which had about 1,851 controllers (742 in the face alone).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In the 2004 film *The Day After Tomorrow*, designers had to design forces of extreme weather with the help of video references and accurate meteorological facts.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] For the 2005 remake of *King Kong*, actor Andy Serkis was used to help designers pinpoint the gorilla's prime location in the shots and used his expressions to model "human" characteristics onto the creature.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Serkis had earlier provided the voice and performance for Gollum in Peter Jackson's *The Lord of the Rings* trilogy.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer animation can be created with a computer and an animation software.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Some impressive animation can be achieved even with basic programs; however, the rendering can require much time on an ordinary home computer.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Professional animators of movies, television and video games could make photorealistic animation with high detail.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] This level of quality for movie animation would take hundreds of years to create on a home computer.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Instead, many powerful workstation computers are used; Silicon Graphics said in 1989 that the animation industry's needs typically caused graphical innovations in workstations.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Graphics workstation computers use two to four processors, and they are a lot more powerful than an actual home computer and are specialized for rendering.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Many workstations (known as a *"render farm"*) are networked together to effectively act as a giant computer, resulting in a computer-animated movie that can be completed in about one to five years (however, this process is not composed solely of rendering).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] A workstation typically costs $2,000 to $16,000 with the more expensive stations being able to render much faster due to the more technologically advanced hardware that they contain.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Professionals also use digital movie cameras, motion/performance capture, bluescreens, film editing software, props, and other tools used for movie animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Programs like Blender allow for people who can not afford expensive animation and rendering software to be able to work in a similar manner to those who use the commercial grade equipment.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The realistic modeling of human facial features is both one of the most challenging and sought after elements in computer-generated imagery.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer facial animation is a highly complex field where models typically include a very large number of animation variables.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Historically speaking, the first SIGGRAPH tutorials on *State of the art in Facial Animation* in 1989 and 1990 proved to be a turning point in the field by bringing together and consolidating multiple research elements and sparked interest among a number of researchers.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The Facial Action Coding System (with 46 "action units", "lip bite" or "squint"), which had been developed in 1976, became a popular basis for many systems.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] As early as 2001, MPEG-4 included 68 Face Animation Parameters (FAPs) for lips, jaws, etc., and the field has made significant progress since then and the use of facial microexpression has increased.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In some cases, an affective space, the PAD emotional state model, can be used to assign specific emotions to the faces of avatars.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] In this approach, the PAD model is used as a high level emotional space and the lower level space is the MPEG-4 Facial Animation Parameters (FAP).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] A mid-level Partial Expression Parameters (PEP) space is then used to in a two-level structure – the PAD-PEP mapping and the PEP-FAP translation model.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Realism in computer animation can mean making each frame look photorealistic, in the sense that the scene is rendered to resemble a photograph or make the characters' animation believable and lifelike.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer animation can also be realistic with or without the photorealistic rendering.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] One trend in computer animation has been the effort to create human characters that look and move with the highest degree of realism.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] A possible outcome when attempting to make pleasing, realistic human characters is the uncanny valley, the concept where the human audience (up to a point) tends to have an increasingly negative, emotional response as a human replica looks and acts more and more human.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Films that have attempted photorealistic human characters, such as *The Polar Express*, *Beowulf*, and *A Christmas Carol* have been criticized as "disconcerting" and "creepy".
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The goal of computer animation is not always to emulate live action as closely as possible, so many animated films instead feature characters who are anthropomorphic animals, legendary creatures and characters, superheroes, or otherwise have non-realistic, cartoon-like proportions.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer animation can also be tailored to mimic or substitute for other kinds of animation, like traditional stop-motion animation (as shown in *Flushed Away* or *The Peanuts Movie*).
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Some of the long-standing basic principles of animation, like squash and stretch, call for movement that is not strictly realistic, and such principles still see widespread application in computer animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The popularity of websites that allow members to upload their own movies for others to view has created a growing community of independent and amateur computer animators.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] With utilities and programs often included free with modern operating systems, many users can make their own animated movies and shorts.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Several free and open-source animation software applications exist as well.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The ease at which these animations can be distributed has attracted professional animation talent also.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Companies such as PowToon and Vyond attempt to bridge the gap by giving amateurs access to professional animations as clip art.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The oldest (most backward compatible) web-based animations are in the animated GIF format, which can be uploaded and seen on the web easily.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] However, the raster graphics format of GIF animations slows the download and frame rate, especially with larger screen sizes.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The growing demand for higher quality web-based animations was met by a vector graphics alternative that relied on the use of a plugin.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] For decades, Flash animations were a common format, until the web development community abandoned support for the Flash Player plugin.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Web browsers on mobile devices and mobile operating systems never fully supported the Flash plugin.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] By this time, internet bandwidth and download speeds increased, making raster graphic animations more convenient.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Some of the more complex vector graphic animations had a slower frame rate due to complex rendering compared to some of the raster graphic alternatives.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Many of the GIF and Flash animations were already converted to digital video formats, which were compatible with mobile devices and reduced file sizes via video compression technology.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] However, compatibility was still problematic as some of the video formats such as Apple's QuickTime and Microsoft Silverlight required plugins.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] YouTube was also relying on the Flash plugin to deliver digital video in the Flash Video format.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] The latest alternatives are HTML5 compatible animations.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Technologies such as JavaScript and CSS animations made sequencing the movement of images in HTML5 web pages more convenient.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] SVG animations offered a vector graphic alternative to the original Flash graphic format, SmartSketch.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] YouTube offers an HTML5 alternative for digital video.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] APNG (Animated PNG) offered a raster graphic alternative to animated GIF files that enables multi-level transparency not available in GIFs.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Computer animation uses different techniques to produce animations.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Most frequently, sophisticated mathematics is used to manipulate complex three-dimensional polygons, apply "textures", lighting and other effects to the polygons and finally rendering the complete image.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] A sophisticated graphical user interface may be used to create the animation and arrange its choreography.
[src:requestanimationframe/computer-animation] Another technique called constructive solid geometry defines objects by conducting Boolean operations on regular shapes, and has the advantage that animations may be accurately produced at any resolution.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In reference to terminology originating with cathode-ray tubes (CRTs), the **refresh rate**, also known as **vertical refresh rate**, **vertical scan rate** or **vertical frequency**, is the number of times per second that a raster-based display device displays a new image.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] This can be independent from frame rate, which describes how many images are stored or generated every second by the device driving the display.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] On CRT displays, higher refresh rates produce less flickering, thereby reducing eye strain.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In other technologies, such as liquid-crystal displays, the refresh rate affects only how often the image can potentially be updated.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Non-raster displays may not have a characteristic refresh rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Vector displays, for instance, do not trace the entire screen, only the actual lines comprising the displayed image, so refresh speed may differ by the size and complexity of the image data.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] For computer programs or telemetry, the term is sometimes applied to how frequently a datum is updated with a new external value from another source (for example; a shared public spreadsheet or hardware feed).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] While all raster display devices have a characteristic refresh rate, the physical implementation differs between technologies.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Raster-scan CRTs by their nature must refresh the screen since their phosphors will fade and the image will disappear quickly unless refreshed regularly.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In a CRT, the vertical scan rate is the number of times per second that the electron beam returns to the upper left corner of the screen to begin drawing a new frame.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] It is controlled by the vertical blanking signal generated by the video controller, and is partially limited by the monitor's maximum horizontal scan rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The refresh rate can be calculated from the horizontal scan rate by dividing the scanning frequency by the number of horizontal lines, plus some amount of time to allow for the beam to return to the top.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] By convention, this is a 1.05x multiplier.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] For instance, a monitor with a horizontal scanning frequency of 96 kHz at a resolution of 1280 × 1024 results in a refresh rate of 96,000 ÷ (1024 × 1.05) ≈ 89 Hz (rounded down).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] CRT refresh rates have historically been an important factor in video game programming.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In early videogame systems, the only time available for computation was during the vertical blanking interval, during which the beam is returning to the top right corner of the screen and no image is being drawn.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Even in modern games, however, it is important to avoid altering the computer's video buffer except during the vertical retrace, to prevent flickering graphics or screen tearing.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Unlike CRTs, where the image will fade unless refreshed, the pixels of liquid-crystal displays retain their state for as long as power is provided.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Consequently, there is no intrinsic flicker regardless of refresh rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Vsync options can eliminate screen tearing by rendering the whole image at the same time.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] On smaller CRT monitors (up to about 15 in or 38 cm), few people notice any discomfort between 60–72 Hz.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] On larger CRT monitors (17 in or 43 cm or larger), most people experience mild discomfort unless the refresh is set to 72 Hz or higher.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] A rate of 100 Hz is comfortable at almost any size.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] However, this does not apply to LCD monitors.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The closest equivalent to a refresh rate on an LCD monitor is its frame rate, which is often locked at 60 fps.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] But this is rarely a problem, because the only part of an LCD monitor that could produce CRT-like flicker—its backlight—typically operates at around a minimum of 200 Hz.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Different operating systems set the default refresh rate differently.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Microsoft Windows 95 and Windows 98 (First and Second Editions) set the refresh rate to the highest rate that they believe the display supports.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Windows NT-based operating systems and their descendants, including Windows 11, set the default refresh rate to a conservative rate, usually 60 Hz.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Most Linux distributions follow the same behavior, but some are able to dynamically set a default based on the monitor's refresh rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Since macOS is normally used exclusively on Apple devices and products, most versions of macOS are locked to 60 Hz with exceptions like later MacBook Pro models.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Some fullscreen applications, including many games, now allow the user to reconfigure the refresh rate before entering fullscreen mode, but most default to a conservative resolution and refresh rate and let you increase the settings in the options.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Old monitors could be damaged if a user set the video card to a refresh rate higher than the highest rate supported by the monitor.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Some models of monitors display a notice that the video signal uses an unsupported refresh rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Some displays support variable refresh rate (VRR), the ability to change their refresh rate on-the-fly.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] VRR can be used to save power by allowing the system to spend less performance rendering frames, a technique seen on some mobile devices like smartphones and laptops.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Some computer monitors feature VRR to lower input latency, typically that of a video game, by delay refreshing of the display until a new frame is sent from the graphics card.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] FreeSync and G-Sync are implementations of VRR seen in AMD and Nvidia's graphics card, respectively.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Beginning in the 2010s, competitive video gaming prompted manufacturers to develop displays with higher refresh rates than the standard 60 Hz.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] This responded to the relationship between display latency and player response time in first-person shooter and real-time strategy games.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The first 144 Hz displays appeared in 2012, with the 24-inch ASUS VG248QE released in 2013.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] At 144 Hz, the monitor reduced frame persistence to approximately 6.9 milliseconds, compared to 16.7 milliseconds at 60 Hz.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The progression continued through the 2010s.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In 2017, ASUS released the ROG Swift PG258Q, one of the first 240 Hz monitors, using a twisted nematic (TN) panel at 1920 × 1080 resolution.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The 240 Hz refresh rate reduced frame persistence to approximately 4.2 milliseconds.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Higher resolutions at 240 Hz proved more demanding for graphics hardware, making full HD the practical standard for this refresh rate category.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In 2020, ASUS released the ROG Swift PG259QN, the first monitor to achieve 360 Hz, using a "Fast IPS" panel rather than the TN panels previously used for high-refresh displays.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In 2023, ASUS introduced the ROG Swift Pro PG248QP, which reached 540 Hz through an overclock of its native 360 Hz "Esports TN" panel.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] At 540 Hz, frame persistence drops to approximately 1.85 milliseconds.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Sustaining such refresh rates required a high-end graphics processor; testing showed that at 540 Hz and 1920 × 1080 resolution, a NVIDIA RTX 4090 could be fully utilized depending on game settings and title demands.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In May 2026, LG Electronics announced the UltraGear 25G590B, marketed as the world's first gaming monitor with a native 1000 Hz refresh rate at full HD (1920 × 1080) resolution, with expected availability in the second half of 2026.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The 24.5-inch display uses an IPS panel with a backlight-based motion blur reduction system.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Unlike earlier 1000 Hz monitor demonstrations that required switching to 1280 × 720 resolution to reach the refresh rate, the 25G590B maintains 1000 Hz performance at native 1080p.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] When LCD shutter glasses are used for stereo 3D displays, the effective refresh rate is halved, because each eye needs a separate picture.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] For this reason, it is usually recommended to use a display capable of at least 120 Hz, because divided in half this rate is again 60 Hz.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Higher refresh rates result in greater image stability, for example 72 Hz non-stereo is 144 Hz stereo, and 90 Hz non-stereo is 180 Hz stereo.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Most low-end computer graphics cards and monitors cannot handle these high refresh rates, especially at higher resolutions.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] For LCD monitors the pixel brightness changes are much slower than CRT or plasma phosphors.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Typically LCD pixel brightness changes are faster when voltage is applied than when voltage is removed, resulting in an asymmetric pixel response time.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] With 3D shutter glasses this can result in a blurry smearing of the display and poor depth perception, due to the previous image frame not fading to black fast enough as the next frame is drawn.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The development of televisions in the 1930s was determined by a number of technical limitations.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The AC power line frequency was used for the vertical refresh rate for two reasons.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The first reason was that the television's vacuum tube was susceptible to interference from the unit's power supply, including residual ripple.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] This could cause drifting horizontal bars (hum bars).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Using the same frequency reduced this, and made interference static on the screen and therefore less obtrusive.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The second reason was that television studios would use AC lamps, filming at a different frequency would cause strobing.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Thus producers had little choice but to run sets at 60 Hz in America, and 50 Hz in Europe.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] These rates formed the basis for the sets used today: 60 Hz System M (almost always used with NTSC color coding) and 50 Hz System B/G (almost always used with PAL or SECAM color coding).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] This accident of chance gave European sets higher resolution, in exchange for lower frame rates.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] However, the lower refresh rate of 50 Hz introduces more flicker, so sets that use digital technology to double the refresh rate to 100 Hz are now very popular.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Another difference between 50 Hz and 60 Hz standards is the way motion pictures (film sources as opposed to video camera sources) are transferred or presented.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] 35 mm film is typically shot at 24 frames per second (fps).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] For PAL 50 Hz this allows film sources to be easily transferred by accelerating the film by 4%.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The resulting picture is therefore smooth, however, there is a small shift in the pitch of the audio.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] NTSC sets display both 24 fps and 25 fps material without any speed shifting by using a technique called 3:2 pulldown, but at the expense of introducing unsmooth playback in the form of telecine judder.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Similar to some computer monitors and some DVDs, analog television systems use interlace, which decreases the apparent flicker by painting first the odd lines and then the even lines (these are known as fields).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] This doubles the refresh rate, compared to a progressive scan image at the same frame rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] This works perfectly for video cameras, where each field results from a separate exposure – the effective frame rate doubles, there are now 50 rather than 25 exposures per second.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The dynamics of a CRT are ideally suited to this approach, fast scenes will benefit from the 50 Hz refresh, the earlier field will have largely decayed away when the new field is written, and static images will benefit from improved resolution as both fields will be integrated by the eye.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Modern CRT-based televisions may be made flicker-free in the form of 100 Hz technology.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Many high-end LCD televisions now have a 120 or 240 Hz (current and former NTSC countries) or 100 or 200 Hz (PAL/SECAM countries) refresh rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The rate of 120 was chosen as the least common multiple of 24 fps (cinema) and 30 fps (NTSC TV), and allows for less distortion when movies are viewed due to the elimination of telecine (3:2 pulldown).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] For PAL at 25 fps, 100 or 200 Hz is used as a fractional compromise of the least common multiple of 600 (24 × 25).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] These higher refresh rates are most effective from a 24p-source video output (e.g.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Blu-ray Disc), and/or scenes of fast motion.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] As movies are usually filmed at a rate of 24 frames per second, while television sets operate at different rates, some conversion is necessary.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Different techniques exist to give the viewer an optimal experience.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] The combination of content production, playback device, and display device processing may also give artifacts that are unnecessary.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] A display device producing a fixed 60 fps rate cannot display a 24 fps movie at an even, judder-free rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Usually a 3:2 pulldown is used, giving a slight uneven movement.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In the case of material shot on video, improvements in smoothness just from having a higher refresh rate may be barely noticeable.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] In the case of filmed material, as 120 is an even multiple of 24, it is possible to present a 24 fps sequence without judder on a well-designed 120 Hz display (i.e., so-called 5-5 pulldown).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] If the 120 Hz rate is produced by frame-doubling a 60 fps 3:2 pulldown signal, the uneven motion could still be visible (i.e., so-called 6-4 pulldown).
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] Additionally, material may be displayed with synthetically created smoothness with the addition of motion interpolation abilities to the display, which has an even larger effect on filmed material.
[src:requestanimationframe/refresh-rate] "50 Hz" TV sets (when fed with "50 Hz" content) usually get a movie that is slightly faster than normal, avoiding any problems with uneven pulldown.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The **`window.requestAnimationFrame()`** method tells the browser you wish to perform an animation.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] It requests the browser to call a user-supplied callback function before the next repaint.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The frequency of calls to the callback function will generally match the display refresh rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The most common refresh rate is 60hz, (60 cycles/frames per second), though 75hz, 120hz, and 144hz are also widely used.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] `requestAnimationFrame()` calls are paused in most browsers when running in background tabs or hidden `<iframe>`s, in order to improve performance and battery life.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The function to call when it's time to update your animation for the next repaint.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` indicating the end time of the previous frame's rendering (based on the number of milliseconds since time origin).
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The timestamp is a decimal number, in milliseconds, but with a minimal precision of 1 millisecond.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] For `Window` objects (not `Workers`), it is equal to `document.timeline.currentTime`.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] This timestamp is shared between all windows that run on the same agent (all same-origin windows and, more importantly, same-origin iframes) — which allows synchronizing animations across multiple `requestAnimationFrame` callbacks.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The timestamp value is also similar to calling `performance.now()` at the start of the callback function, but it is never the same value.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] When multiple callbacks queued by `requestAnimationFrame()` begin to fire in a single frame, each receives the same timestamp even though time has passed during the computation of every previous callback's workload.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] An `unsigned long` integer value, the request ID, that uniquely identifies the entry in the callback list.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] You should not make any assumptions about its value.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] You can pass this value to `window.cancelAnimationFrame()` to cancel the refresh callback request.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] In this example, an element is animated for 2 seconds (2000 milliseconds).
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The element moves at a speed of 0.1px/ms to the right, so its relative position (in CSS pixels) can be calculated in function of the time elapsed since the start of the animation (in milliseconds) with `0.1 * elapsed`.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The element's final position is 200px (`0.1 * 2000`) to the right of its initial position.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The following three examples illustrate different approaches to setting the zero point in time, the baseline for calculating the progress of your animation in each frame.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] If you want to synchronize to an external clock, such as `BaseAudioContext.currentTime`, the highest precision available is the duration of a single frame, 16.67ms @60Hz.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] The callback's timestamp argument represents the end of the previous frame, so the soonest your newly calculated value(s) will be rendered is in the next frame.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] This example waits until the first callback executes to set `zero`.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] If your animation jumps to a new value when it starts, you must structure it this way.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] If you do not need to synchronize to anything external, such as audio, then this approach is recommended because some browsers have a multi-frame delay between the initial call to `requestAnimationFrame()` and the first call to the callback function.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] This example uses `document.timeline.currentTime` to set a zero value before the first call to `requestAnimationFrame`.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] `document.timeline.currentTime` aligns with the `timestamp` argument, so the zero value is equivalent to the 0th frame's timestamp.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] This example animates using `performance.now()` instead of the callback's timestamp value.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestanimationframe] You might use this to achieve slightly higher synchronization precision, though the extra degree of precision is variable and not much of an increase.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] Since October 2024, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] The **`requestVideoFrameCallback()`** method of the `HTMLVideoElement` interface registers a callback function that runs when a new video frame is sent to the compositor.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] This enables developers to perform efficient operations on each video frame.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] The callback function that runs when a new video frame is sent to the compositor.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time when the callback was called.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time when the browser expects the frame to be visible.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A number, in media pixels, representing the height of the video frame (the visible decoded pixels, without aspect ratio adjustments).
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A number, in seconds, representing the media presentation timestamp of the presented frame.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] This is equal to the frame's timestamp on the `HTMLMediaElement.currentTime` timeline.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time when the browser submitted the frame for composition.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A number representing the number of frames submitted for composition so far alongside the current callback.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] This can be used to detect whether frames were missed between callback instances.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A number, in seconds, representing the duration between the submission of the encoded packet with the same presentation timestamp as this frame to the decoder (i.e., the `mediaTime`) and the decoded frame being ready for presentation.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A number, in media pixels, representing the width of the video frame (the visible decoded pixels, without aspect ratio adjustments).
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time when the frame was captured.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] This applies to video frames coming from a local or remote source.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] For a remote source, the capture time is estimated using clock synchronization and RTCP sender reports to convert RTP timestamps to capture time.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the time when the encoded frame was received by the platform.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] This applies to video frames coming from a remote source.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] Specifically, this corresponds to the time when the last packet belonging to this frame was received over the network.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A number representing the RTP timestamp associated with this video frame.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] A number representing a unique callback ID.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] This can be passed to `HTMLVideoElement.cancelVideoFrameCallback()` to cancel the callback registration.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] Typical use cases for `requestVideoFrameCallback()` include video processing and painting to a canvas, video analysis, and synchronization with external audio sources.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] Per-frame processing used to be done in a less efficient or accurate fashion by running operations on the current video display whenever the `timeupdate` event fired.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] This technique did not provide access to the actual video frames.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] `requestVideoFrameCallback()` is used in the same way as `Window.requestAnimationFrame()`.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] You use it to run a callback function that performs some operation when the next video frame is sent to the compositor.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] The callback finishes by calling `requestVideoFrameCallback()` again to run the callback when the next video frame is composited, and so on.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] One thing to bear in mind is that `requestVideoFrameCallback()` does not offer any strict guarantees that the output from your callback will remain in sync with the video frame rate.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] It may end up being fired one vertical synchronization (v-sync) later than when the new video frame was presented.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] The API runs on the main thread, while video compositing likely happens on a separate compositing thread.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] You've got to factor in the time taken for these operations to complete, as well as the time it takes for the video itself and the result of your `requestVideoFrameCallback()` operation to display on the screen.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] You can compare the `now` callback parameter and the `expectedDisplayTime` metadata property to determine whether your callback is a v-sync late.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] If `expectedDisplayTime` is within about five to ten microseconds of `now`, the frame is already rendered.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] If the `expectedDisplayTime` is approximately sixteen milliseconds in the future (assuming your browser/screen is refreshing at 60Hz), then the callback is a v-sync out.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] This example shows how to use `requestVideoFrameCallback()` to draw the frames of a video onto a `<canvas>` element at exactly the same frame rate as the video.
[src:requestanimationframe/requestvideoframecallback] It also logs the frame metadata to the screen for debugging purposes.
